segments.text: We're going to beat that rascal this year.
We know that a number of the students who were in schools at the time you were there had various and sundry jobs.
Were you ever employed while you were a student?
Oh, for three months I calibrated electric meters there in the electrical engineering department.
That was all.
But quite a few of the boys did have that kind of thing.
Can you recall some of the kinds of things that they did?

old janitor work and that kind of thing and over in the creamery and probably in the dairy barn and and oh I don't know it seemed like it might have been a minority of those boys and they were probably busy at the job and off somewhere and you just didn't notice it too much.
I was wondering did any of them ever work for any of the professors?
You mean in the professor's home?
Yeah, or do things around.
Of course, I guess the college maintained the houses since they owned them.
Oh, yes.
Well, not in the professor's homes.
They might have, but I don't know anything about it.
At that point, I guess there wasn't a whole lot of babysitting to do.
At a later period, I think some of them did babysitting for the faculty.
Well, in that day and time, I don't think there's much babysitting going on because I didn't know about it.
Did the students who played on the college football and baseball and basketball teams and so forth have privileges that the other students didn't have?
Oh, yes.
They had what they called, one thing was the mess hall.
They called it the training table.
And of course, they got special stakes and those kind of things, and that kind of thing.
I don't believe they had to attend Reveille in the morning.
You know, they had Reveille every morning, get out and exercise.
I don't believe they had to go through that.
And they were, a lot of times they were excused from
the evening formation, you know, because they didn't get back in time in that kind of time.
They were excused from quite a few things like that.
They almost had to be in order to participate.
What about, were they, were the officers as strict on them as far as their uniform inspection and so forth is concerned?
Oh, yes, I think so.
I was in the Signal Corps the last year I was there, and Ruby Drake was one of the greatest tackles we ever had down there.
Well, he dressed just like the rest of us, and they inspected him just like they did the rest of us.
I know about him because he was, you know, some of them, they might have been a little more lax on, but not Ruby Drake.
Okay, during the, I guess this would have been what, during your junior year was when they had the most active participation in the First World War.
What changes did this bring about as far as your experiences were concerned?
Well, it brought about quite a few changes because it went back down in the fall of 1918.
registered for school.
That was when the World War was on then.
And, you know, all the upperclassmen had gone to these training camps, these juniors and seniors, and that left just about all that was there was the freshmen and we sophomores.
And
Of course, they had these young lieutenants come in there to train us, that kind of thing, and some of them was only two, three years older than we were, you know.
And it was different in a way.
We tried to maintain all the customs and those kind of things, but it was a noticeable difference, I think, during that period.
But it didn't last long, thank goodness.
I believe it only lasted from like September of 1918 to what, the beginning of the next term.
Yes, that's right, the next term.
You know, we were all enlisted in the Army there, sworn in, probably about the first of October 1918, and then they discharged shortly after the Armistice, probably early December.
I don't remember the exact date.
Were you enlisted in what was called the SATC?
SATC, Student Army Training Corps, yes, sir.
And you still attended GLSIS, I take it?

Oh yes, we did, and that's right, and we specialized on military, you know, and these officers would talk to us and train us, and they'd begin to sort us out to go to future training camps in case the war continued.
I was slated to go to an artillery camp, but you know, the war ended before I reached that point.
And I think the, particularly the seniors who came back were,
enrolled in in January, and they did kind of a hurry up two semesters.
Hurry up a semester.
I think they ran over in June sometime.
But it hurried up to get them through there and to graduate them.
And so actually, you didn't really have any participation in the war effort other than being in the SATC for a couple months.
That's right, on the campus, a couple months.
Let's see.
I noticed here from your senior yearbook, you were in G Company, what, the first regiment?
Yes, sir.
For three years?
Yes, sir.
And let's see.
Company of Signal Corps after that.
Okay.
I have you being as a fish in Company G1 and a sophomore in Company G1, and then you were in a sergeant in G Company, and then you went to first sergeant in A Company Signal Corps.
Right, right.
When was that, when did you switch to the signal corps?
Was that... That was January 1919 when the seniors came back.
I was a first sergeant.
That period from January to June.
So it was kind of, so did all the students then go through June instead of not just the seniors?
The whole college.
The whole college went until June.
And then a lot of us went to camp, military camp.
I went back with a group back to Louisville, Kentucky to an infantry camp after the war, right after June.
Right after June until then you came back in September again for the senior year, and then you were captain in the Signal Corps then.
Company A.
So that's when you got your free pass to the theater.
Oh, yes.
You were also, I take it, in the RVs.
Yeah, I was in the RV, yes, sir.
Fine organization.
What?
Fine organization.
What was the procedure for becoming a member of the RVs?
Well, it was a secret ballot.
Of course, I didn't know my name written proposed.
I don't know who proposed it.
These RVs, they met and then they announced who they had elected to join the organization.
And that was in the afternoon, they announced it.
And of course, the RVs then went over cases, which was a confectionery in that Y, in order to box cigars or peas or drinks and charge it to the new RVs.
And of course, we had to divide up and pay the bill.
So I knew nothing about it until I was notified I'd been elected.
A happy occasion.
What sort of things did the RVs do?
Well, of course, they had a dance every year.
They called it the RV dance.
And then we had special drills, military drills, precision drills.
And then at the end of the year, we'd compete on these drills, who would be the best drill man, and that kind of thing.
That was within the RVs?
Yes, RVs.
So you had kind of a double amount of drilling to do then, as you remember.
Were you in the RVs as both a junior and a senior?
No.
No, my senior year, my senior year.
But I believe both juniors and seniors were eligible.
Yes, they were, but mine, junior year, I mean senior year.
Was that generally the case, most of them were seniors?
Well, I'd say...
I'd say the majority of them were yes.
Yes, I think so.
Although, you know, they had a nucleus to come on next year to carry the organization on.
I think there's more than 50% of them seniors, yes, as I recall.
So then you had a special uniform which you wore just occasionally.
Yes, that's right.
He has a white uniform and gold braid and all that kind of stuff.
You wore this to the RV hop and other occasions.
Yeah, the RV hop, yeah, that's right, and the drills and...
special occasions that we dressed in the Army uniform.
And I noticed you were also a member of the senior court.
Yes, I was.

In those days, instead of the military office punishing boys, they decided for a while after this senior court made up of seniors to find out what was going on and the circumstances and mete out punishment.
to these guilty persons.
And we'd bring the boys in and question them and find out both sides, just like a regular court.
And then they'd issue a punishment.
And of course, the cadet colonel and some of those were on top of it.
And they had a couple of commanders on the thing.
They tried to get it all over so they'd have representation.
But how many were on the senior court?
Oh, I'd say
Might have been 20, not over 20, as I recall.
This would have been then, say, after the World War I, when they did the senior court?
Yes, oh yes.
That was my senior year.
To my knowledge, they didn't have it before then.
They might have.
But what sort of infractions would the senior court work upon?
The violations of military discipline?
Well, yes, and then staying over in Brown, maybe without pass, or going without pass, or...
Now I know one case, one of the upperclassmen made a very derogatory remark, there's company command there.
Well, they, things like that, you know, bring that up and thrash that out.
What did you do then?
Did you, you would decide upon punishment, would this be issuing a certain amount of demerits?
Demerits, that kind of thing, or yes, maybe sometimes they'd confine them to campus too, you know, and confine them to campus, demerits.
Were these demerits then announced at the evening meal as had been the custom before?
A couple of people I've talked to said every night at supper they read the RAM list for the day.
I don't recall that they read the special.
No, I don't recall that.
And I don't recall the RAM list at mealtime.
I don't recall that.
I might do that another period, you know.
Not in my time.
I don't remember.
Mm-hmm.
I don't think they did.
Okay.
I noticed that you have a picture of Bevo there with the 13-0 branded on him.
Yes, sir.
And this incident occurred while you were there, I take it.
No.
Well, this branding did, yes.
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, branding did.
It was a 1915 game.
That's why I was there.
But seniors went over to him in 1916, I believe it was.
They went over to Austin, cut old Bevo, and branded him there, 13-0.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, I believe that was early in 1917 they did that.
My assistant has talked with Hans...

roadie from hondo oh yeah he was one of them i believe yeah he wielded the branding iron i believe oh well and here's um here's a picture there's um goodman hall and this is some this is gone yeah that's gone now that's the drill field nowadays you know back there here's the over see the old building entrance this view this way this was the main entrance back out of the old building is now was the sewer
Now, did that fence go all the way around the campus?
No, no, just the gate there, just the gate.
Just the gate right there at the entranceway from near the railroad track.
The railroad track's both right over here, two of them, you know.
There was not a road between the railroad track and the...
Today, there's a paved highway that runs from Bryan through Welburn, and I believe it runs all the way to Navasota.
I believe there's a road between the railroad tracks and this gate, I believe, at that time, yes, coming from Bryan.
Yes, because that's the only way to get to Bryan in those days.
You didn't have that other road, no.
Yeah, it wasn't paved.
No, it was gravel probably.
Okay.
Here, did you ever see this picture?
That's the Rye Sal.
Did you ever see that?
I have seen a different picture of it.
I haven't seen this one.
Well, that, you know, we got that in 1916.
Here's a uniform we wore in 1916, see?
This is Spieser Hall.
And we had this thing locked up on the fourth floor, I believe, the Old Main, which was the Army at that time, and the sergeants guarded.
But, you know, I guess you heard this story.
The Rice boys came up there and captured this thing.
And I've always thought that the...
The feds at the university got together.
They didn't want to keep this thing, so they said, you send your boys up and we'll make sure you get it.
Well, our boys chased them, they said, all the way back to Houston trying to catch them, but they never caught them.
Rodie, I think, told us a little bit about that.
He said something about that Rice boys had hired a detective.
to come over and investigate.
And he supposedly posed as a sports writer and found out where it was and let the Rice boys know where it was.
Well, I don't know the details.
I always thought maybe Dr. Brazell got with the president of Rice and said, well, now we've had our fun.
Come and get it.
I don't know what he said.
Well, it's always a possibility.
That's right.
Here's the, that's what you look like in those days.
Let me ask you this question.
Over here from the left, there's a track.
Is this the Tunerville Trolley track through here?
Let me see.
Where's the mess hall?
Let me see.
The mess hall was on.
Oh, yeah, right here.
Yeah, right here.
You boarded it right over here, just west of it.
That was the termination of it.
And then it went right out this way over to Bryan.
And this was a spur from one or the other, either the INGN or the HNTC, I guess, to bring...
I suppose so, yes, to bring the material and things into the station, college.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
Let's go back to this picture of Bevo for a minute, and let me ask you about this.
We have on one copy, we have two or three copies of this picture in the archives, and on the back of one, there's a couple of clippings.
One of the clippings indicates that sometime after this branding, Bevo was slaughtered.
They had a banquet over at Austin in January of 1920, to which some people from A&M and people from the University of Texas were invited.
They had a barbecue banquet over at the gymnasium in Austin.
And since that supposedly occurred when you were there, I wondered if you heard anything about it.
a banquet of that nature.
No, if I knew about it, it would slip my mind.
I don't recall that.

Well, we have this clipping that's not dated, but we also have an invitation that's the size of a regular sheet of paper, 8 12 by 11, has a picture of Bevo before the branding, plus an invitation at the bottom which indicates that he was slaughtered, and he was January 22, 1920.
I see.
I don't recall that.
I'll tell you one incident happened over at Austin, I remember, when I was about a sophomore.
A whole bunch of them went over there.
We were playing basketball at the University of Texas in their gym.
And I believe it was between the half, we were on one side and the T-Sips on the other side.
And they turned a possum loose on that court with our colors on it.
Well, you know what happened.
To my knowledge, the game was never finished.
I wasn't there when it finished anyway.
How we got back to College Station, I don't remember.
But I imagine you had a general melee.
A general meeting, anyway.
Oh, boy, gosh.
Okay, then you graduated then in the spring or May or June of 1920.
May the 20th, 1920.
And did you then
have a job at the time you graduated, or did you enter the job market at that point?
No, City Service sent a representative down to College Station in the spring of 1920 to interview people, and three of us in the class signed up.
But when we got out of school in the May, we were committed to
for our ROTC commitment to attend a signal corps camp back in Little Silver, New Jersey.
So we went back there and I took up my employment in first September by agreement with city service.
And where did you go for your first job?
Bartleville, Oklahoma.
That was the headquarters of the city service oil company at that time.
Okay, and I think you said you were with city service?
42 years in 711.
42 years in 711.
So you never worked for anybody else?
Nobody.
Could you tell me a little bit about what you did for city service?
Well, I worked in the other department, except the treasurer wouldn't trust me there.
But I worked in the... We started out, we had a junior engineer's course, kind of a training course where they'd send you around to all the departments, kind of get acquainted and learn how.
Then I was in the engineering department.

surveying and drafting and things like that and then I was in the pipeline department kind of overseeing or supervising contractors who were laying pipelines for us and then at that time we had an appraisal department that appraised all of our properties and I was serving that department as an engineer and then I when I then in 19 then
In the early 40s, the Federal Power Commission started cracking down all the utilities to get them to establish the original cost and that kind of thing.
And I served in the rates department of our company several years, establishing original cost and that kind of thing with companies.
And I put in the last 19 years my tenure as a subsidiary of the City Service Gas Company in Oklahoma City in the rates and sales department.
OK.
um then you you retired from city service uh what year 60 and retired april 1st 1963.
63. did you move directly to amarillo at that point well when i retired we put our house for sale up in
Oklahoma City and since I've been camping out for two years, native Texan, I want to get back to Texas.
My wife, all her family lived here.
Her son lived in Denver.
Well, we put her house up for sale and in about five months we sold it and moved here and bought this house.
So it was because of family then that you, family connections, that you moved down the road?
Well, yes.
I visited here many, many times, wife, brothers, and we loved the climate here.
It was a wonderful climate.
Best in the country.
Best in the world.
Where did you meet your wife?
I met her in Bartlesville, Oklahoma.
She was working for city service when I joined the organization, and I met her there.
Okay, Bartlesville was the headquarters, national headquarters?
Well, no, New York City was the national headquarters, but Bartlesville was the next headquarters for the oil company activities.
Okay.
What sort of things have you been involved in since you have come to Amarillo?
Well, of course, I belong with the...
local camera club in Oklahoma City and I've continued my activities in the camera club here.
I put our slides up to judge and score.

One year I was president of the American Association of Retired Persons organization here in town and I attend and take part in Sunday school and church activities every week and on politics I distribute pamphlets and call on the neighbors and that kind of thing to
get them out to vote, and do a little gardening and keep up my yard.
But you haven't actually entered politics yourself.
No, no, I don't intend to.
No, no.
They'll deliver me.
No, no.
Well, I think you had one more picture there.
Oh, here's the Aggie team in 1919, Southwest Champions.
See, that's all the players we had.
Well, that wouldn't even make the watering squad now.
Yeah.
You know, in 19...
As I recall, DX, we played Texas University at College Station.
We had one coach, DX, an assistant, and a colored ball for the rubdown.
That's all we had.
And he coached track or something else.
I can't recall whether this is a fact, but DX put in 11 players.
And if I recall correctly, he didn't have a timeout or a substitution.
You might check that someplace.
Mm-hmm.
Well, I think they were much stricter on what you could have in the, for, you know, I think at that point you couldn't call a timeout just because you wanted to.
No, and if you played in one quarter and come out, you couldn't go back in that quarter.
And we beat them seven to nothing, and we marched right on through.
But, boy, we had some real old boys in those days.
Here's old, here's old Kempmutter.
Boy, yeah.
What's that little figure written?
Well, that looks like somebody standing way back there in the background, looks like.
Let's see.
Here's Harrison right here.
You know, he lives over in Brown.
Chick Harrison.
You know Chick Harrison?
R.H. Harrison?
He's a class agent with the class of 20.
He lives in Brown, isn't he?
I don't know him personally.
I probably have heard of him.
Chick Harrison.
R.H. Harrison.
Yeah.
Okay.
Okay.
I guess that was the high point in A&M athletics when they had... Well, in 1917, they weren't scored on either.
Right here.
That tells the story.
This was... Well, that's 1919.
Well, in 1917, they weren't scored on either.
So you had 1917, and the 1919 football teams were not scored on at all?
No, they weren't.
We played LSU.
This is my wife.
This is Mr. Sheward.
How you do?
Well, he's been asking me all kinds of questions.
Did you?
Well, yeah, you want to fix one?
